post_text:
Congratulations to recent WA graduate Isabella McLellan for being named the recipient of a $2,000 scholarship as a result of her blood drive efforts while she was enrolled at Parkway West Career and Technology Center last school year.

The PWCTC Health Occupations Technology Program earned points from the Central Blood Bank for each blood drive held at PWCTC, which equates to student scholarships. The scholarship is typically announced at the end of each school year; however, due to COVID-19, they were just recently awarded.

Isabella was a member of the National Technical Honor Society.

post_text:
West Allegheny is pleased to launch Canvas, the District’s new Learning Management System for parents and students in grades K-12.

To get you started, our very own Dr. Cheryl McHone created the four-minute tutorial video below that provides helpful tips, guidelines and an overview of Canvas features. In addition to the desktop application, Canvas also offers an App with both Android and iOS support, which we recommend downloading free from the App Store. Both platforms allow families convenient and timely access to student attendance, schedules, assignments, grades, calendars, teachers and much more once school begins.

Later this evening, parents/guardians should receive an individual email for each of your children that provides a unique pairing code generated by the District that is necessary for you to access your child's Canvas account.

We look forward to seeing how our students, staff and parents engage with this dynamic learning platform.

https://vimeo.com/channels/1192788/448906288

Every morning, before each student leaves for school, families are asked to help with the important job of monitoring student health. The Home Health Screen link below contains questions and guidelines to help decide when to keep your child home.

We recommend printing the document and posting it in a convenient place for easy reference.

Please note that if your child stays home as a result of answering “yes” to any of the questions on the form, you must call your school nurse before your child returns to the school.

http://www.westasd.org/Downloads/Home%20Health%20Screen%202020-2021%208%2020%202020.pdf

The District’s Educational Delivery Option Commitment Survey submissions are due by this Friday, July 31.

Your survey responses will be instrumental in the District's ability to plan for staffing each of the instruction models and prepare for a successful learning experience for your child(ren).

Thank you for your cooperation!

post_text:
West Allegheny's Students In Action group demonstrated their compassionate and caring nature as they thanked frontline healthcare workers by creating care packages that were delivered to three local hospitals..

In addition to collecting items for the packages, the students also wrote over 30 letters each thanking healthcare workers for their sacrifices and giving them words of encouragement.

On Friday, faculty advisors Kennan Grabner and Kateri Meinert delivered seven boxes of treats, and hundreds of handmade cards to essential workers at Shadyside, West Penn, and Mercy Hospitals to thank them for their unparalleled commitment during this challenging time.

post_text:
As announced previously, West Allegheny School District has been approved to provide meal service during the school closure to families in need without requiring prior approval. We are pleased to share that our dedicated and caring food service team has provided over 14,400 meals to date.

Given the governor's directive that individuals be required to wear a protective mask when in public, we are requiring families who are participating in the meal program to wear a mask/covering upon pick-up. This added measure, along with practicing social distancing, will further ensure the health and safety of our essential and greatly appreciated food service team.

We sincerely thank you for your cooperation.

post_text: We are so proud to announce that high school assistant principal, Cheryl McHone, has earned her doctorate degree after successfully defending her dissertation on March 27. Her dissertation topic was titled Blended Learning Integration: Student Motivation and Autonomy in a Blended Learning Environment and her degree was completed through East Tennessee State University. Dr. McHone joined the District at the start of the 2018-2019 school year. Kudos!

Her dissertation topic was titled Blended Learning Integration: Student Motivation and Autonomy in a Blended Learning Environment and her degree was completed through East Tennessee State University. Dr. McHone joined the District at the start of the 2018-2019 school year. Kudos!

post_text:
Awesome News!

West Allegheny was selected as one of the Best Communities for Music Education for 2020 by the NAMM Foundation for the 3rd consecutive year. WA is one of 754 districts across the nation recognized for outstanding efforts by music teachers, administrators, parents, students and community leaders who have made music education part of a well-rounded education and demonstrate an exceptionally high commitment and access to music education. This award reflects the positive interactions and overall synergy between the WA music program and the district communities throughout the year.

post_text:
In an effort to keep our WA Family updated, please see the communication below from the Pennsylvania Department of Education:

"Pennsylvania Department of Education (PDE) will be announcing a cancellation of statewide assessments for the 2019-2020 school year. This cancellation includes the PSSA, PASA, and Keystone Exams.

We understand that during these unprecedented circumstances, school communities across the state are managing more pressing issues on the education landscape, like providing access to food and nutrition, and putting appropriate systems in place to continue student learning. Assessments should not be the focus of school leaders right now."

post_text:
Please see the communication below that was shared with McKee families last night:

The District was alerted today that a custodian at McKee Elementary School who was seen at a local hospital, was diagnosed with acute bronchitis and told to self-quarantine due to a lack of available testing for COVID-19. The employee is an evening custodian and was not exhibiting signs of illness until Monday of this week. Out of an abundance of caution, McKee Elementary School will be closed to all staff and visitors until further notice. Meal and device pick-up for school families that was originally scheduled at McKee will now be available at the high school cafeteria entrance from 10:00 a.m. to 12:00 p.m. each week day.

post_text: This past Tuesday, leaders from our Students in Action club presented at the annual SHASDA Student Forum. West Allegheny’s representatives were Ava Pustover, Kayleigh Bayer, Luke Boni, and Robert Moran. Kateri Meinert served as the faculty representative and Kennan Grabner attended as well. The students presented on their initiatives this year, including the WAHS Day of Caring and blood drives, student led presentations, AERIE grant, and West A. & Co. program. Over twenty school districts attended and were able to learn from our students.

post_text: A group of Stand Together members traveled to the Convention Center today for a Youth Mental Health Advocacy Workshop at the Disability and Mental Health Summit with other students, mental health leaders, and state legislators. Students listened to keynote speakers from around the county, participated in student led discussion groups, and had a chance to present to state legislators to voice their concerns about changes needed in the area of mental health supports and school funding. Our students were vocal and did a great job advocating for equality between physical health and mental health!

Representatives from Moe’s Southwest Grill were also on hand to present a grant for almost $500 worth of playground equipment. A sincere thank you to all who made this possible!!

post_text: The District’s Wellness and Safe Schools Committee sponsored assemblies at the middle school last week on the dangers of vaping. The one-hour program was a live theater performance from the Saltworks Theater Company. Their goal was to use the production to educate, challenge and inspire students to make healthy choices. Members of Students in Action kicked off the performances by introducing the “Spread the Word to Stop the Word” campaign as they promoted inclusiveness of individuals with disabilities.

Preschool students from the high school were so excited to get a visit from the North Fayette Fire Department yesterday. They taught the children about fire safety and what firefighters look like when they enter a house that’s on fire wearing all their equipment. The students were also invited to explore the firetruck while learning about how it works.

A huge thank you to the North Fayette Fire Department for their informative visit!

post_text: Our three elementary schools hosted Family Math Nights over the past three weeks with the theme ‘We Love Math.” The math focused evenings were full of puzzles, games, and challenges for families to participate in together. The events highlighted the importance of math while engaging students and their families in important mathematical skills such as problem solving, mental math, estimation, basic operations, and fact fluency. With over 700 in attendance over the three nights, the response was amazing. Dr. Kim Buser and Dr. Shana Nelson worked with staff to organize the events.

post_text: Today our students, who are members of Stand Together, facilitated “WHAPP Day” in the high school. “WHAPP” stands for the common signs and symptoms of mental illness: withdrawal, hopelessness, agitation, personality changes, and poor self-care. Staff and Stand Together members wore Stand Together WHAPP shirts to raise awareness about mental health. In addition, students in Stand Together painted their faces with handprints, to signify “WHAPP” and start the conversation regarding mental health. In classes, students of Stand Together provided their peers with mini classroom presentations related to the signs and symptoms, and how to reach out for help if a student is experiencing such symptoms. Stand Together continues to support and promote the awareness of mental health while reducing the stigma surrounding this topic. Kudos to Erica Cicero, Meredith Gillo, Laura Montecalvo, Angela Devereaux, Lisa Monzo, and Katie Zanella, our Stand Together advisors.

post_text:
The middle school Horizons students recently attended the annual Science Bowl at The Carnegie Museum of Natural History. The competition is a science based academic competition for students in grades 6-8 and is sponsored by the Allegheny Intermediate Unit. West Allegheny had three teams representing the middle school with two teams placing.

Congratulations to the 7th grade team of Zach Lebak, Ashlee Lebak, and Alicia Stierheim for claiming a 1st place to win the competition.

And our 8th grade team consisting of Cassie Wolfe, Hope Fronczek, Josie Mercier, and Eva Lutz came in 3rd place.

Congratulations to all of our participants.

#WAStudentStrong
